[In the past 24 hours, since the last update, there have been 66 new cases
and 10 new deaths reported. Of the deaths, 9 were from Hong Kong and one
from Singapore. As of 15 Apr 2003 the cumulative totals are 3235 cases and
154 deaths, reported from 22 countries. Of note, there were no reports of
new cases from China. As there has been significant speculation about
spread of SARS throughout China, one wonders whether this is a real "no
cases" versus there was "no reporting" in the past 24 hours. We look
forward to further information on the collaborative investigations in China.
The discussion surrounding the "super-spreaders" in today's WHO update
[1][C] is very interesting and logical (so much for theories proposed by
this moderator in yesterday's posting as well as earlier postings, albeit
this was just in response to earlier suggestions on the part of the
official agencies suggesting there were "super-spreaders"). According to
reports on the epidemiologic studies (which we have not seen as yet) the
"super spreaders" were observed early on in the outbreak when infection
control procedures had not been implemented. Many of the second-generation
cases in Hong Kong, Singapore, and Canada were related to contact within
the health care environment. Logically, with the introduction of infection
control procedures in the health care environment, this risk has been
markedly reduced. It would be very interesting to see diagrammatic
representations of the spread in the various locations where studied (such
as was presented in the 28 Mar 2003 MMWR article presenting the analyses
of the cases resulting from contact in Hotel M in Hong Kong
<http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5212a1.htm>) for additional
individuals responsible for multiple next-generation cases, by type of
contact spread involved, and date of onset of symptoms.
The newswires were filled with articles related to SARS, the overwhelming
majority offering no new information not available on the official websites
and presented here. There has been much mention of the economic impact of
this outbreak in terms of industries affected, most notably the travel
industry. This would include the airlines of the affected countries as
well as other airlines from Europe, the United States, and Australia that
have noted significant declines in traffic attributable to both SARS and
political events. Clearly in the global village we now live in, major
outbreaks have global economic impact. - Mod.MPP]
